.\" gostow(8) -- gostow's own prose, deliberately.
.\"
.\" GNU Stow's stow.8 is generated by Pod::Man from bin/stow's POD. stow is
.\" GPLv3 and gostow is MIT, so reproducing that page's expression would be both
.\" a licence violation and a lie about authorship. What gostow reproduces is
.\" *behaviour* -- option names, their semantics, the diagnostics, the exit codes
.\" -- which no licence governs. See NOTICE and docs/SPEC.md section 4.5.
.\"
.\" Neither of GNU Stow's two option references is complete: `stow --help` never
.\" mentions --no-folding, and stow.8 never mentions --compat/-p. This page
.\" documents every option gostow's parser accepts, and a test proves it --
.\" internal/cli/docs_test.go compares this file against spec().
.TH GOSTOW 8 "2026-07-10" "gostow" "System Administration Commands"
.
.SH NAME
gostow \- install and remove packages of files by symbolic link
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B gostow
[\fIOPTION\fR ...] [\fB\-D\fR|\fB\-S\fR|\fB\-R\fR] \fIPACKAGE\fR ...
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B gostow
is a reimplementation of GNU Stow 2.4.1 as a single static binary. It installs a
.I package
by creating symbolic links in a
.I target
directory that point back at the package's own files, and removes a package by
deleting exactly the links that point into it.
.PP
Because the target holds only links, several packages may be installed into one
directory tree and each removed again independently. This is what makes it
useful for two quite different jobs: keeping
.IR /usr/local
tidy when software is built from source, and keeping a directory of dotfiles
under version control while the files appear in
.IR $HOME .
.PP
.B gostow
plans an entire invocation before it touches the disk. If any package would
conflict, nothing is written and every conflict is reported at once, so a run
either succeeds completely or changes nothing.
.PP
Where a package's subdirectory does not yet exist in the target,
.B gostow
links the directory itself rather than its contents. This is called
.IR folding ,
and it keeps the number of links small. When a second package needs to install
into that same directory, the fold is undone automatically: the link is replaced
by a real directory and both packages' contents are linked inside it.
.PP
Aside from color on a terminal,
.B gostow
is byte-for-byte compatible with GNU Stow: same options, same output, same exit
codes, same links. See
.B DIVERGENCES
below.
.
.SH TERMINOLOGY
.TP
.I stow directory
The directory holding the packages, one subdirectory per package. Set with
.BR \-d ,
else
.BR $STOW_DIR ,
else the current directory.
.TP
.I package
One subdirectory of the stow directory. Its contents are the
.IR "installation image" :
the tree that should appear, as links, under the target.
.TP
.I target directory
Where the links are created. Set with
.BR \-t ,
else the parent of the stow directory.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Directories
.TP
.BI \-d " DIR" "\fR, \fP" \-\-dir= DIR
Use
.I DIR
as the stow directory instead of the current directory. This also changes the
default target, which is the stow directory's parent.
.TP
.BI \-t " DIR" "\fR, \fP" \-\-target= DIR
Use
.I DIR
as the target directory instead of the stow directory's parent.
.
.SS Actions
Actions apply to the packages that follow them, so a single command may stow one
package and unstow another.
.TP
.BR \-S ", " \-\-stow
Install the packages that follow. This is the default, and may be omitted unless
the command mixes actions.
.TP
.BR \-D ", " \-\-delete
Remove the packages that follow, deleting only links that point into them.
.TP
.BR \-R ", " \-\-restow
Remove, then reinstall. Use this to prune links left behind by files a package
no longer contains.
.
.SS Choosing files
.TP
.B \-\-dotfiles
Translate a leading
.RB \(lq dot\- \(rq
in a package file's name to a literal
.RB \(lq . \(rq,
per path component. The package file
.I dot\-vimrc
is installed as
.IR .vimrc ,
so a dotfile repository need contain no hidden files.
.TP
.BI \-\-ignore= REGEX
Do not install files whose path
.I ends
with a match for
.IR REGEX .
May be given more than once. These patterns are additive and are checked before
any ignore list file.
.TP
.BI \-\-defer= REGEX
Do not install files whose path
.I begins
with a match for
.IR REGEX
if some other package has already installed them. May be given more than once.
.TP
.BI \-\-override= REGEX
Install files whose path begins with a match for
.IR REGEX
even if another package installed them, replacing that package's links. May be
given more than once.
.PP
Each
.I REGEX
is an RE2 regular expression (Go's
.I regexp
syntax), not a Perl one. Lookaround and backreferences are rejected at parse
time rather than silently matching something else; inline flags such as
.RB \(lq (?i) \(rq
work. GNU Stow's own ignore patterns, and every pattern in a
.I .stow\-local\-ignore
or
.IR .stow\-global\-ignore ,
compile unchanged.
.
.SS Behavior
.TP
.B \-\-adopt
When a target file already exists as a plain file, and so belongs to no package,
move it into the package and link it back into place. The file's contents
survive; the package's copy is overwritten.
.B This rewrites your stow directory.
Commit first.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-folding
Never fold a directory into a single link. Create the directory in the target
and link its contents individually, and do not refold a directory that becomes
foldable during removal.
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-compat
Remove packages by scanning the whole target tree for links that point into
them, rather than by walking the package's own installation image. This is the
older algorithm. It is slower, and it will remove a link that points into the
package even if the package no longer contains the file.
.
.SS Output
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-no ", " \-\-simulate
Plan the run and report what would happen, without modifying anything.
.TP
.BR \-v "[" \fIN\fR "], " \-\-verbose [=\fIN\fR]
Increase verbosity. Levels run from 0 to 5;
.B \-v
adds one level each time it is given, while
.BI \-\-verbose= N
sets the level outright. Verbose output goes to standard error.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Print the version and exit.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print a summary of the options and exit.
.
.SS gostow extensions
This option does not exist in GNU Stow. It is prefixed
.RB \(lq gostow\- \(rq
and may not be abbreviated, so no command line that GNU Stow accepts is parsed
differently here.
.TP
.B \-\-gostow\-fix
Correct GNU Stow's known defects instead of reproducing them. Without this flag
.B gostow
reproduces them faithfully, because a drop\-in replacement that quietly behaves
better is still behaving differently. The
.B DIVERGENCES
section below is the exact list.
.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success, including a simulated run.
.TP
.B 1
The command line was rejected, a directory named by
.B \-d
or
.B \-t
does not exist, no packages were named, or the run was abandoned because of
conflicts.
.TP
.B 2
A fatal error: a package is missing from the stow directory, a package name is
malformed, or a configuration file is unusable.
.PP
GNU Stow's fatal exit status is whatever
.I errno
the last failing system call happened to leave behind \(em 255 when there was
none.
.B gostow
always exits 2, because a status that depends on the last syscall is not a
status a script can test.
.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B STOW_DIR
The stow directory, when
.B \-d
is not given. A
.B \-\-dir
setting in a resource file overrides it.
.TP
.B HOME
Locates
.I ~/.stowrc
and
.IR ~/.stow\-global\-ignore .
.TP
.B NO_COLOR
If set to any value, suppress color. Color is emitted only when standard
output is a terminal, so a pipe or a redirect is unaffected either way.
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.IR ~/.stowrc ", " ./.stowrc
Resource files. See
.B RESOURCE FILES
below.
.TP
.I <stow_dir>/<package>/.stow\-local\-ignore
Ignore patterns for one package.
.TP
.I ~/.stow\-global\-ignore
Ignore patterns for every package.
.
.SH RESOURCE FILES
Both
.I ~/.stowrc
and
.I ./.stowrc
are read, in that order, and their contents are concatenated and parsed as if
they were one list of command line arguments preceding the real ones. For an
option that takes a single value, the last occurrence wins, so
.I ./.stowrc
overrides
.IR ~/.stowrc ,
and the real command line overrides both.
.PP
GNU Stow's manual states the opposite order. Its code does what is described
here, and
.B gostow
follows the code.
.PP
Each line is split into words as a shell would split them, honouring quotes and
backslash escapes.
.B There is no comment syntax.
A
.RB \(lq # \(rq
is an ordinary word, and the words after it are read as package names \(em which
a resource file discards. Comments therefore appear to work, by accident.
Actions and package names in a resource file are parsed and then ignored.
.PP
Values given to
.B \-\-dir
and
.B \-\-target
undergo variable and tilde expansion:
.IR $VAR ,
.IR ${VAR} ,
.IR ~ ,
and
.IR ~user .
A backslash escapes any of them. Referring to an environment variable that is
not set is a fatal error.
.
.SH IGNORE LISTS
Three sources of ignore patterns exist, and
.B only the first that exists is used.
They are not merged.
.IP 1. 4
.I <stow_dir>/<package>/.stow\-local\-ignore
.IP 2. 4
.I ~/.stow\-global\-ignore
.IP 3. 4
A built\-in list, covering version control metadata
.RI ( .git ,
.IR .svn ,
.IR CVS ,
.IR RCS ,
.IR _darcs ,
.IR .hg ),
editor and merge debris
.RI ( *~ ,
.IR #*# ),
and, at the top of a package only,
.IR README* ,
.I LICENSE*
and
.IR COPYING .
.PP
So creating
.I ~/.stow\-global\-ignore
discards the built\-in list entirely, and a package's
.I .stow\-local\-ignore
discards both. Patterns given with
.B \-\-ignore
are additive and are applied before any of the three.
.PP
In an ignore file, blank lines and lines beginning with
.RB \(lq # \(rq
are skipped, a trailing comment is stripped, and
.RB \(lq \e# \(rq
is a literal
.RB \(lq # \(rq.
A pattern containing no
.RB \(lq / \(rq
is matched against each path component on its own; a pattern containing one is
matched against the path relative to the package root. A package's
.I .stow\-local\-ignore
never installs itself.
.
.SH DIVERGENCES
.\" The body of this section is generated from docs/DIVERGENCES.md by
.\" internal/mangen (go generate ./...). Do not edit between the markers; edit
.\" the doc and regenerate. A test fails if this copy drifts.
.\" BEGIN GENERATED DIVERGENCES
.\" Imported from docs/DIVERGENCES.md by internal/mangen; do not edit here.
.\" Edit docs/DIVERGENCES.md and run: go generate ./...
.PP
gostow is a drop\-in replacement for GNU Stow 2.4.1. Run it with no special flags and it produces the same symlinks, the same output, and the same exit codes \(em bugs included. Every claim on this page is enforced by a test that runs the real \fBstow\fP binary alongside gostow and compares stdout, stderr, exit code, and the resulting directory tree.
.PP
The differences are listed exhaustively below.
.SS Things gostow fixes without being asked
.PP
These are defects, not behavior. Nobody's script depends on them, and reproducing them would mean shipping a tool that breaks in ways stow breaks. gostow does not reproduce any of them, ever, with or without flags.
.PP
\fBGNU Stow does this\fP: \fBDies if your home directory contains a \fB(\fP, \fB[\fP, \fB+\fP, \fB*\fP, or \fB?\fP.\fP \fB$HOME\fP is pasted into a regular expression unescaped, so \fBHOME=/home/o'brien(2)\fP kills stow before it does any work, at any verbosity.
.br
\fBgostow does this\fP: Runs normally. gostow never builds that expression.
.PP
\fBGNU Stow does this\fP: \fBAborts an entire unstow because some unrelated symlink points at the text \fB0\fP.\fP Perl reads the string \fB"0"\fP as false, so a perfectly readable link is reported as unreadable. Exit code 2, nothing removed.
.br
\fBgostow does this\fP: Reads the link and carries on.
.PP
\fBGNU Stow does this\fP: \fBSilently disables \fIall\fP ignore rules if \fB.stow\-local\-ignore\fP exists but cannot be read.\fP Your \fBREADME.md\fP gets stowed, and the unreadable ignore file stows itself. Exit code 0, no warning.
.br
\fBgostow does this\fP: Fails loudly: \fBgostow: ERROR: cannot read ignore file ...\fP, exit 2.
.PP
\fBGNU Stow does this\fP: \fBExits with whatever error number the last failed system call left behind\fP \(em 2 here, 255 there, depending on the machine.
.br
\fBgostow does this\fP: Every fatal error exits 2.
.PP
\fBGNU Stow does this\fP: \fBStows into a directory you never named when a \fB~username\fP fails to resolve.\fP \fB\-\-target=~nosuchuser/tmp/x\fP in a \fB.stowrc\fP expands the unknown user to nothing, leaving \fB/tmp/x\fP, and stow builds the symlink farm there. Exit code 0.
.br
\fBgostow does this\fP: Leaves the path alone, so it fails the ordinary check: \fB\-\-target value '~nosuchuser/tmp/x' is not a valid directory\fP, exit 1, nothing written.
.PP
\fBGNU Stow does this\fP: Contains code paths that would crash or silently corrupt its own bookkeeping if they were reachable. They are not reachable.
.br
\fBgostow does this\fP: Those paths are simply not written.
.PP
There are also three differences that are not bugs being fixed:
.IP \(bu 3
\fB\fBgostow \-\-version\fP reports gostow's version\fP, naming the stow release it clones: \fBgostow 0.1.1 (GNU Stow 2.4.1 compatible)\fP. Reporting \fB2.4.1\fP for a binary released as \fB0.1.1\fP would be theatre.
.IP \(bu 3
\fB\fBgostow \-\-help\fP is written in gostow's own words.\fP It documents the same options, with the same names and the same meanings, and it also documents \fB\-\-no\-folding\fP \(em a real, working flag that stow's own help has never mentioned. The old help block was stow's, copied byte for byte, which had two problems: stow is GPLv3 and gostow is MIT, and the copied text ended \fBReport bugs to: bug\-stow@gnu.org\fP, so gostow was sending its own bug reports to somebody else's mailing list.
.RS 3
.PP
Nothing a script reads changed. Option \fIparsing\fP is still byte\-exact, the usage diagnostic on stderr is still byte\-exact, and so is the exit code. The test suite checks that every option GNU Stow documents, gostow documents too.
.RE
.IP \(bu 3
\fBA bad \fB\-\-ignore\fP, \fB\-\-defer\fP or \fB\-\-override\fP pattern is reported in gostow's words.\fP Real stow lets Perl's regex engine complain, and Perl names a line number inside \fB/usr/bin/stow\fP. gostow says \fBInvalid \-\-ignore regex "(": ...\fP. Everything a script can observe is identical: the pattern is rejected while the command line is being parsed, so it is caught even when you named no packages; the usage block goes to stdout; the exit code is 1; and two bad patterns still produce two complaints.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBgostow colors its output when it is talking to a terminal.\fP Real stow never does. Nothing else in this document is additive; this is, because it cannot reach a script. Color appears only when the stream is a terminal, and it only ever wraps text that was already there \(em take the escapes back out and you have stow's bytes, exactly. Redirect to a file, pipe it anywhere, or set \fBNO_COLOR\fP to any non\-empty value, and gostow emits not one escape character. \fBTERM=dumb\fP disables it too.
.RS 3
.PP
The slogan is \fIbyte\-compatible on a pipe, prettier on a TTY\fP. The test suite proves the first half directly: over every shape of line gostow prints, stripping the escapes from a colored line returns the uncolored line exactly, and when color is off the coloring pass does not run at all.
.RE
.SS Things gostow reproduces, and \fB\-\-gostow\-fix\fP corrects
.PP
These are quirks a script could, in principle, be relying on. They are reproduced faithfully by default. Pass \fB\fB\-\-gostow\-fix\fP\fP to get the sensible behavior instead.
.PP
\fBGNU Stow does this\fP: \fB\fB\-\-dotfiles\fP walks straight past a \fB.stow\fP\-protected directory when stowing\fP \(em and creates files inside it \(em while unstowing correctly refuses to touch it. The files are stranded there permanently. This is a real protection bypass.
.br
\fB\fB\-\-gostow\-fix\fP does this\fP: Honours the guard when stowing, exactly as it already does when unstowing.
.PP
\fBGNU Stow does this\fP: \fB\fBstow \-\- mypackage\fP silently discards \fBmypackage\fP\fP and dies with \fBNo packages to stow or unstow\fP.
.br
\fB\fB\-\-gostow\-fix\fP does this\fP: Treats the arguments after \fB\-\-\fP as package names.
.PP
\fBGNU Stow does this\fP: \fB\fB.stowrc\fP has no comment syntax.\fP A \fB#\fP is an ordinary word. Bare words after it become package names and are quietly dropped, which is why comments \fIseem\fP to work \(em but anything option\-shaped after a \fB#\fP is silently obeyed. \fB\-\-ignore=keep # \-\-ignore=drop\fP really does ignore \fBdrop\fP.
.br
\fB\fB\-\-gostow\-fix\fP does this\fP: \fB#\fP begins a comment. \fB\e#\fP is a literal \fB#\fP.
.PP
\fBGNU Stow does this\fP: \fB\fBRMDIR /some/path\fP\fP prints without a colon, while \fBLINK:\fP, \fBUNLINK:\fP, \fBMKDIR:\fP and \fBMV:\fP all have one.
.br
\fB\fB\-\-gostow\-fix\fP does this\fP: \fBRMDIR:\fP gets its colon.
.SS Things gostow reproduces, and does not yet fix
.PP
Two of stow's own documented bugs. Fixing them is real work on the algorithm, not a flag, so \fB\-\-gostow\-fix\fP leaves them alone today.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBThe empty\-directory problem.\fP Unstowing one package can remove a directory that another, still\-installed package needs.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBFolding across stow directories.\fP A folded symlink pointing into a \fIdifferent\fP stow directory does not split open when a second package needs it.
.PP
Two more differences are outside stow's control, and outside gostow's:
.IP \(bu 3
The wording of \fBValue "abc" invalid for option verbose (...)\fP comes from Perl's \fBGetopt::Long\fP, not from stow, and changed between Perl releases. gostow pins the current wording.
.IP \(bu 3
At verbosity 3 and above, stow prints traces of its own Perl call structure. gostow is a different program inside and prints different traces. Verbosity 0 through 2 \(em the levels any script would read \(em are byte\-for\-byte identical, and gostow's higher verbosities always still contain those lines, in order.
.SS Things gostow cannot do
.PP
One, and it is a property of the regex engine rather than a decision.
.PP
\fBPerl regexes with lookaround or backreferences are rejected.\fP Go's regular expressions run in time linear in the input and cannot backtrack, which is what makes them immune to the catastrophic blow\-ups a hostile pattern can provoke in Perl. The price is that \fB\-\-ignore='x(?!y)'\fP and \fB\-\-ignore='(k)\e1'\fP compile in stow and not in gostow.
.PP
gostow rejects the pattern rather than quietly matching something else:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
$ gostow \-\-ignore='x(?!y)' mypackage
Invalid \-\-ignore regex "x(?!y)": error parsing regexp: invalid or unsupported Perl syntax: `(?!`
.EE
.RE
.PP
\&...followed by the usage block, exit code 1 \(em the same as any other unusable pattern. Ordinary patterns are unaffected, including inline flags like \fB(?i)\fP, and every pattern in stow's built\-in ignore list, in \fB.stow\-local\-ignore\fP and in \fB.stow\-global\-ignore\fP compiles unchanged.
.PP
If a real \fB.stowrc\fP ever needs lookaround, the fix is a backtracking engine used for that pattern alone. Nobody has produced one yet.
.SS Things gostow installs under its own name
.PP
\fB\fBman gostow\fP, not \fBman stow\fP.\fP gostow ships a manual page and completions for bash, zsh and fish, all named after \fBgostow\fP. It does not answer to stow's names, and that is deliberate rather than an oversight.
.PP
The pages and scripts live at paths a package owns: \fB/usr/share/man/man8/stow.8\fP, \fB/usr/share/bash\-completion/completions/stow\fP, \fB/usr/share/fish/vendor_completions.d/stow.fish\fP. Those belong to the \fBstow\fP package. Installing our own files there would be a file conflict in apt and dnf, and it would silently replace GNU Stow's manual on any machine that has both. gostow is a drop\-in replacement for the \fIbinary\fP, not a replacement for the \fIpackage\fP \(em it does not claim the name \fBstow\fP in any namespace, including apt, dnf, and completion.
.PP
Nor can the second name simply be registered from inside gostow's own file, except in zsh. Bash and fish autoload a completion by opening a file named after the command being completed, so the registration would never run. Registering it in zsh alone would give a completion that appears in one shell and not the others, which is worse than none.
.PP
If you have symlinked \fBstow\fP to gostow, opt in from your shell's rc file:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
complete \-F _gostow stow            # bash
compdef _gostow stow                # zsh, after compinit
complete \-c stow \-\-wraps gostow     # fish
.EE
.RE
.PP
GNU Stow ships no completions of its own, so nothing is being overridden. And gostow's manual page documents every option gostow accepts \(em which is more than either of GNU Stow's own references manages, since \fBstow \-\-help\fP omits \fB\-\-no\-folding\fP and \fBstow.8\fP omits \fB\-\-compat\fP.
.\" END GENERATED DIVERGENCES
.
